{"id":41604,"title":"GERD: body position affects infant GER but not symptoms.","abstract":"Increased gastro-oesophageal reflux (GER) is described as a very common problem in infants. Loots et al. investigated the effect of the left lateral position on reflux and symptoms, finding that body position affects GER but not symptoms. The data highlight the difficulties faced in investigating reflux disease in the paediatric population.","date":"2014-07-02","categories":"Digestive System Diseases","split":"train","url":"http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/24912388","annotations":[{"name":"Infant","weight":0.782496,"wikipedia_article":"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Infant"},{"name":"Disease","weight":0.706228,"wikipedia_article":"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Disease"},{"name":"Symptom","weight":0.46934,"wikipedia_article":"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Symptom"},{"name":"Proprioception","weight":0.311533,"wikipedia_article":"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Proprioception"},{"name":"Pediatrics","weight":0.257612,"wikipedia_article":"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pediatrics"},{"name":"Anatomical terms of location","weight":0.115641,"wikipedia_article":"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Anatomical_terms_of_location"},{"name":"Gastroesophageal reflux disease","weight":0.0627902,"wikipedia_article":"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gastroesophageal_reflux_disease"},{"name":"Population","weight":0.0543856,"wikipedia_article":"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Population"},{"name":"Data","weight":0.0147415,"wikipedia_article":"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Data"},{"name":"Germany","weight":0.0144926,"wikipedia_article":"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Germany"}]}
